The pink shadings indicate that these levels have too few observations and the levels are merged for final analysis.

The final classification for the predictors that may potentially have any influence on Creditability.

  • “Creditability” = Good(1), Bad(2)

  • “Duration.of.Credit..month.” = Continuous

  • “Purpose” = Car(1), Home Relase(2), Other(3)

  • “Value.Savings.Stocks” = None(1), Below 100 DM(2), 100,1000, Above 1000(4)

  • “Instalment.per.cent” = Above 35%(1), (25%, 35%](2), [20%, 25%)(3), Below 20%(4)

  • “Guarantors” = None(1), Yes(2)

  • “Most.valuable.available.asset” = None(1), Car(2), Life Insurance(3), Real Estate(4)

  • “Concurrent.Credits” = Other Bank or Dept Store(1), None(2)

  • “No.of.Credits.at.this.Bank” = 1 (1), 2 and Above(2)

  • “No.of.dependents” = 3 or more(1), less than 3(2)

  • “Foreign.Worker” = No(1), Yes(2)

  • “Account.Balance” = No Account(1), No Balance(2), Some Balance(3)

  • “Payment.Status.of.Previous.Credit” = Some Problem(1), Paid Up(2), No Problem(3)

  • “Credit.Amount” = Continuous

  • “Length.of.current.employment” = Below 1 Year include unemployed(1), [1,4)(2), [4,7)(3), Above 7(4)

  • “Sex…Marital.Status” = Male Single and Divorce(1), Male Married and Widow(2), Female(3)

  • “Duration.in.Current.address” = <1 Year(1), [1,4)(2), [4,7)(3), Above 7(4)

  • “Age..years.” = Continuous

  • “Type.of.apartment” = Free(1), Rent(2), Owned(3)

  • “Occupation” = Unskilled(1), Skilled(2), Executive(3)

  • “Telephone” = No(2), Yes(1)

Prepare Data for Training

Setting the factor Before training the binary classification models

clean_df$Creditability <- factor(clean_df$Creditability, 
                                 levels = c(0,1), 
                                 labels = c("Bad", "Good"))
clean_df$Creditability <- as.ordered(clean_df$Creditability)

Create function to Split Data for use in Training Models and Validation Models

# Split data

split_data <- function(data, p) {
  set.seed(444)
  n <- nrow(data)
  id <- sample(1:n, size = n*p)
  train_df <- data[id, ]
  test_df <- data[-id, ]
  return(list(train_df = train_df, test_df = test_df))
}

split_credit <- split_data(clean_df, 0.7)
train_df <- split_credit$train_df
test_df <- split_credit$test_df

split data train_df and test_df with probabilty = 0.7 for train data and probability = 0.3 for test data \[\\[1in]\]

III. Train/ Evaluate Models

And then before train model, I have set the train Control which mean the resampling method. For all models, I use the K-fold Cross Valoidation instead Bootstrap the set as default in caret train function.

#set the resamples method 
# use K-fold Cross validation 
ctrl_cv <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                        number = 5,
                        verboseIter = TRUE)

Logistic Regression

#1. Logistic Regression 
glm_m1 <- train(Creditability~
                 Account.Balance + 
                 Payment.Status.of.Previous.Credit +
                 Purpose +

Summary

Accuracy and AUC are measures to evaluate the goodness of model performance. But due to our dataset the Creditability are imbalance, the proportion of Good = 0.7 and Bad = 0.3. In this case AUC is good choice, because AUC is well-suited for imbalanced datasets.According to this reason, Random Forest have the maximum AUC.
